            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this card making calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool is designed for card makers who want quick, accurate
                measurements without doing paper math every time. It combines
                the most useful features from separate “cards per sheet”,
                envelope, and box-envelope calculators into one place.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Cards per sheet & cutting layout</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator treats your sheet and card as rectangles and
                tries to tile as many cards as possible in both portrait and
                landscape orientations.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Step 1 – Effective sheet size</strong></p>
                <p>
                  We subtract margins and cutting gaps (kerf) from the sheet:
                </p>
                <p>
                  \(W_\text{eff} = W_\text{sheet} - 2 \cdot \text{margin}\)<br />
                  \(H_\text{eff} = H_\text{sheet} - 2 \cdot \text{margin}\)
                </p>
                <p><strong>Step 2 – Card footprint</strong></p>
                <p>
                  If it’s a folded card, we double the dimension along the fold.
                  For example, a 4.25 × 5.5 in top-fold card is cut as 4.25 × 11
                  in before scoring.
                </p>
                <p><strong>Step 3 – Fit counts</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(n_x = \left\lfloor \dfrac{W_\text{eff} +
                  \text{gap}}{W_\text{card} + \text{gap}} \right\rfloor\)<br />
                  \(n_y = \left\lfloor \dfrac{H_\text{eff} +
                  \text{gap}}{H_\text{card} + \text{gap}} \right\rfloor\)
                </p>
                <p>Total cards per sheet: \(N = n_x \cdot n_y\).</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The tool compares portrait vs. landscape and reports the better
                option, along with a simple text-based cutting plan you can
                follow with a trimmer or guillotine.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Envelope sizing</h3>
              <p>
                For a flat envelope, we add a small clearance around the card so
                it slides in easily, then compute a punch-board style layout.
              </p>
              <p>The internal envelope size is:</p>
              <p>
                \(W_\text{env} = W_\text{card} + 2 \cdot c\)<br />
                \(H_\text{env} = H_\text{card} + 2 \cdot c\)
              </p>
              <p>
                where \(c\) is the clearance. From this, the calculator derives
                a square (or near-square) starting sheet and the score positions
                for the side and top/bottom flaps.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Box envelopes for dimensional cards</h3>
              <p>
                Box envelopes add depth so you can mail cards with foam tape,
                flowers, or shaker elements. The internal dimensions are:
              </p>
              <p>
                \(W_\text{box} = W_\text{card} + 2 \cdot c\)<br />
                \(H_\text{box} = H_\text{card} + 2 \cdot c\)<br />
                \(D_\text{box} = T_\text{card} + 2 \cdot c\)
              </p>
              <p>
                The flat sheet size and score lines are then calculated so that,
                once folded, the internal space matches these dimensions.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Paper usage & cost</h3>
              <p>
                Once you know how many cards fit per sheet, you can estimate how
                many sheets and packs you need for a project or for selling card
                sets.
              </p>
              <p>Sheets required:</p>
              <p>
                \(\text{sheets} = \left\lceil \dfrac{\text{cards
                needed}}{\text{cards per sheet}} \right\rceil\)
              </p>
              <p>Packs of cardstock:</p>
              <p>
                \(\text{packs} = \left\lceil \dfrac{\text{sheets}}{\text{sheets
                per pack}} \right\rceil\)
              </p>
              <p>
                The same logic is used for envelopes if you choose to include
                them.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical tips for card makers</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Plan for test cuts:</strong> When trying a new size,
                  add one extra sheet for test cuts and mistakes.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Consider grain direction:</strong> For folded cards,
                  score and fold with the paper grain for cleaner folds.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Batch your projects:</strong> Use the paper usage tab
                  to see how many cards you can make from a full pack of
                  cardstock.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Save your favorite sizes:</strong> Note down your best
                  layouts (e.g., “A2 top-fold – 4 cards per Letter sheet”) for
                  future projects.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>
                Can I use this for A2, A6, A7 and other common card sizes?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Just enter the finished card size in inches or centimeters.
                The calculator is not limited to any specific standard; it works
                with any rectangle.
              </p>

              <h3>What if my trimmer can’t cut very narrow strips?</h3>
              <p>
                If the cutting plan shows very thin waste strips that are hard
                to cut accurately, increase the margin or cut gap slightly and
                recalculate. This will reduce the number of cards per sheet but
                make cutting easier.
              </p>

              <h3>Does this account for printer margins?</h3>
              <p>
                If you print designs directly onto the sheet before cutting, set
                the margin to at least your printer’s non-printable border so
                that no design is cut off.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Can I use this for digital cutting machines (Cricut,
                Silhouette)?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Use the dimensions from the calculator when setting up your
                design space. The cards-per-sheet result tells you how many
                copies to place on your virtual mat to match your cardstock
                size.
              </p>
            </section>
